### 4.3 ABLATION STUDIES AND ANALYSIS  

Best- of- n sampling. We explore using a best- of- n approach by sampling with temperature \(\tau = 1\) and the jailbreak template, where the highest score on \(n\) attempts is reported. We show the results in Table 2 and, as expected, observe significant improvements in model performance. GPT- 4o's harm score increases from \(70.7\%\) to \(83.7\%\) (best- of- 5), while Claude 3.5 Sonnet improves from \(65.1\%\) to \(79.7\%\) (best- of- 5). Notably, Mistral exhibits the most substantial enhancement, with its harm score rising from \(67.4\%\) to \(90.8\%\) (best- of- 5). We note Mistral demonstrates notably higher variability in its responses, with a standard deviation of \(\pm 8.5\%\) . We observe lower average scores when using \(\tau = 1\) instead of \(\tau = 0\) .  

Effect of prompting. We explore the effect of different prompting techniques: chain- of- thought, ReAct, and a refusal- inducing prompt. We show harm scores and refusal rate with these prompting techniques in Table 3 and refer to Appendix B. Refusals increase with CoT and ReAct prompting when no attack is used, even for Mistral. When using a basic prompt to encourage refusing harmful prompts, we see substantial improvements in refusals as seen in Anil et al. (2024) for standard single

